This project visualizes CPU, RAM, and SSD power data on a website using Django, Highcharts, and MongoDB. 

This software was developed using Ubuntu 10.10.
To use this software,

1. Install mongodb and pymongo:
    sudo apt-get install mongodb, python-pymongo

2. Create the data directory for mongodb:
    sudo mkdir /data
    sudo mkdir /data/db

3. Install Django by going to their website:
    http://www.djangoproject.com/download/
    or
    sudo apt-get install python-django

4. Start the mongodb server on a port. The following using port 90:
    sudo mongod --port 90

5. To load test data into Mongodb taken from our Atom servers,
    run test_data/parse_server_output.py with output_shorter.daq2 as input:

    python parse_server_output.py < output_shorter.daq2


6. Unfortunately, the Django developers have taken a pretty firm stance
    against relative paths:
      http://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/694

    Therefore, before starting the Django server, edit ABS_PATH inside
    Server_data_visualization/settings.py to the path corresponding to your 
    project directory (Visualize-Server-Data)

7. DAQ instructions (if you plan on using the daq instead of the test_input):
    Navigate to cmd directory and edit the ABS_PATH (same as before) in 
    cmd/config.h and compile with:
    
    gcc daq.c -lcomedi -lm -lpthread -o daq

8. To start Django, in Server_data_visualization run:
    python manage.py syncdb
    python manage.py runserver

9. To see the website, type

    http://127.0.0.1:8000/power/

    into a web browser and enjoy.

